# A calculating table or frame; an instrument for performing [[arithmetical]] [[calculations]] by balls [[sliding]] on wires, or [[counters]] in grooves, the lowest line representing units, the second line, tens, etc. {{defdate|First attested in the late 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=2}}</ref>
#: {{ux|en|I've heard merchants still use an '''abacus''' for adding things up in China.}}
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=1888|author=Walter William Rouse Ball|title=A Short Account of the History of Mathematics|page=119|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=p9zuAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA119|passage=The '''abacus''' is obviously only a concrete way of representing a number in the decimal system of notation, that is, by means of the local value of the digits.}}
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=1888|author=Walter William Rouse Ball|title=A Short Account of the History of Mathematics|page=123|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=p9zuAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA123|passage=We may there find some slight attempts at a study of literature, but mathematics was never read: to learn the use of the '''abacus''', to keep accounts, and to know the rule by which the date of Easter could be determined was all the science that the most studious aimed at.}}
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=2008|author=Valerie Anand|title=The House of Lanyon|page=55|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=C9N_pfW8MgUC&pg=PA55|passage=She's handy with a loom and an '''abacus''', as well.}}
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=2008|author=Valerie Anand|title=The House of Lanyon|page=209|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=C9N_pfW8MgUC&pg=PA209|passage=She was sitting at the parlour table with a small '''abacus''' in front of her.}}
# {{lb|en|architecture}} The [[uppermost]] portion of the [[capital]] of a [[column]], immediately under the [[architrave]]. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=2005|title=The Classical Orders of Architecture|edition=2nd|page=76|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=YWCnUT0-5xwC&pg=PA76|passage=The '''abacus''' is moulded in three sections and has four main concave faces corresponding with the tapering volutes below and truncated by a short sqaure face on the diagonal.}}
# A board, tray, or table, divided into [[perforated]] [[compartments]], for holding cups, bottles, or the like; a kind of [[cupboard]], [[buffet]], or [[sideboard]]. {{defdate|First attested in the late 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>

